## 3. `branch` — Cross-Cutting Field (New in v1.2)

**Context:** Shiksharthi currently operates (or will operate) **3 branches**:

| Branch | Classes Offered |
|---|---|
| Pubali | 7–10 |
| Baguipara | 11–12 |
| Chinar Park | 7–10 |

**Build sequencing:** The system is being built for **Baguipara only** right now. That's a fine MVP scoping decision — but it must not be a *hardcoded* one. If `branch` isn't modeled as a first-class field from day one, every entity (students, batches, rooms, faculty assignments, fees, schedules) will need to be retrofitted later, and historical Baguipara-only data will need a risky backfill migration to attach it to a branch. Modeling it now costs very little; bolting it on later costs a migration project.

**Rule:** Every entity that is currently scoped to "the institute" should instead be scoped to "a branch within the institute."

### Recommended implementation note
Create a **`Branch` reference table** (`id`, `name`, `address`, `class_range`, `is_active`) with rows for Pubali, Baguipara, and Chinar Park (the other two can be marked `is_active = false` or simply unused until rollout — no need to build their workflows yet, just reserve the structural slot).

### Entities that must carry `branch_id`

| Entity | Why |
|---|---|
| **Students** | A student belongs to one branch (enrollment is branch-specific, just as it's year-specific). |
| **Batches** | Batch names can repeat across branches in theory (though with today's class ranges, "12 JEE A" only exists at Baguipara) — branch scoping prevents ambiguity and future-proofs against name collisions if Pubali/Chinar Park ever add senior-secondary batches. |
| **Rooms** | Room numbers (0–7) are **local to Baguipara**. Pubali and Chinar Park will have their own room numbering/capacity sets. Without `branch_id` on Room, a "Room 3" lookup is meaningless once a second branch is added. |
| **Schedule** | A weekly slot is branch + room + batch specific. |
| **Faculty** | Faculty may be branch-exclusive or may teach across branches (e.g., a Physics mentor splitting time between Baguipara and Chinar Park) — model as a many-to-many `FacultyBranchAssignment`, not a single field, so cross-branch faculty aren't a special case later. |
| **Fees** | Package pricing is very likely to differ by branch and by class range (a Class 8 fee structure has nothing to do with a Class 12 JEE package). |
| **User Accounts (Admin/Mentor)** | Reception staff and mentors are realistically tied to a physical location. Each user account should have a **home branch** (or a list of branches they're permitted to access). Director accounts should default to **all branches**. |

### Permission implication (ties into Section 7)
Once a second branch goes live, Admin and Mentor visibility should default to **their assigned branch only** — a Pubali receptionist should not see Baguipara fee data by default. Director remains the only role with cross-branch visibility out of the box. This should be modeled as a `branch_id` (or `branch_ids[]`) on the user record, checked alongside the existing role-based permission flags (Section 7) — i.e., access = role permission **AND** branch match.

### Academic structure is NOT shared across branches
This is the part most likely to cause confusion if missed: the **Class 11–12 / JEE–NEET–Boards package structure documented in Section 4 is entirely a Baguipara concept.** Pubali and Chinar Park serve Classes 7–10, which almost certainly need a different model entirely:
- Different subject set (likely no separate JEE/NEET packages at the middle-school level — possibly a single standard curriculum per class, e.g. Class 8: English, Math, Science, Social Studies).
- Different batch-naming convention (e.g., "Class 8 A" rather than "12 JEE A").
- Possibly no "package" concept at all — flat per-class fee instead of JEE/NEET/Boards package logic.

**Recommendation:** Don't try to force-fit the Baguipara JEE/NEET package model onto Classes 7–10 when those branches are built. Treat "Academic Structure" (Section 4) as **branch-specific configuration**, not a single global structure — i.e., `Class`, `Batch`, `Subject`, and `Package` should all be scoped under a branch, even though only Baguipara's is defined today.

