### A.4 `Student` ↔ `Enrollment` Split (Implemented)

Because Class Promotion (Section 5.3) and Branch/Batch Transfer (Sections 5.2, 5.3) each create a *new* academic record rather than overwriting the old one, `branch_id`, `class`, `batch_id`, and `status` belong on a separate per-year **Enrollment** record — not on the permanent **Student** identity record. This is what makes "show me this student's full history across branches and years" a simple join, instead of a query that has to reconstruct history from overwritten fields.

#### `Student` — permanent identity, one row per real human, never deleted

| Column | Type | Constraints | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `id` | UUID / INT (PK) | Primary Key, auto-generated | |
| `student_code` | VARCHAR(20) | Unique, Not Null | Human-readable global ID, e.g. `SH-0001` — stays the same across every promotion/transfer for the student's entire time at the institute |
| `name` | VARCHAR(150) | Not Null | |
| `parent_name` | VARCHAR(150) | Nullable | |
| `date_of_birth` | DATE | Nullable | |
| `gender` | VARCHAR(20) | Nullable | |
| `address` | TEXT | Nullable | |
| `admission_date` | DATE | Not Null | First-ever admission date, across all years/branches |
| `created_at` | TIMESTAMP | Not Null, Default now | |
| `updated_at` | TIMESTAMP | Not Null, auto-update | |

> **No mobile number field** — per Director instruction, neither the student's nor the parent's contact number is stored anywhere on this table (or anywhere else in the schema). This is no longer a blocker for Module 12 (Section 8) — that module raises internal alerts only, to in-app roles; the Head of Shiksharthi (who has no account in this system) is informed manually and handles parent contact entirely outside Shiksharthi OS.

#### `Enrollment` — one row per (`student_id`, `academic_year_id`)

| Column | Type | Constraints | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `id` | UUID / INT (PK) | Primary Key, auto-generated | |
| `student_id` | UUID / INT | FK → `Student.id`, Not Null | |
| `academic_year_id` | UUID / INT | FK → `AcademicYear.id`, Not Null | |
| `branch_id` | UUID / INT | FK → `Branch.id`, Not Null | |
| `class` | VARCHAR(10) | Not Null | e.g. `11`, `12` (or `7`–`10` once Pubali/Chinar Park are live) |
| `batch_id` | UUID / INT | FK → `Batch.id`, Not Null | |
| `package_type` | VARCHAR(20) | Nullable | `JEE`, `NEET`, `Boards`, or null for branches without package logic (Section 3) |
| `add_on_subjects` | JSON / linked table | Nullable | e.g. `["Computer Science"]` |
| `status` | VARCHAR(30) | Not Null, Default `Active` | One of: `Active`, `Leave of Absence`, `Batch Transfer`, `Branch Transfer`, `Class Promotion`, `Completed`, `Dropped Out` — per Section 5.1 |
| `status_effective_date` | DATE | Not Null | Date the current status took effect (transfer date, leave start date, etc. — per Sections 5.2–5.6) |
| `previous_enrollment_id` | UUID / INT | FK → `Enrollment.id`, Nullable | Self-reference linking to the prior year/batch/branch record — this is what makes a student's full chain (e.g. `11 JEE @ Baguipara 2025–26` → `12 JEE A @ Baguipara 2026–27`) traversable in one recursive query |
| `created_at` | TIMESTAMP | Not Null, Default now | |
| `updated_at` | TIMESTAMP | Not Null, auto-update | |

**Unique constraint:** (`student_id`, `academic_year_id`) should be unique — a student has exactly one active enrollment per academic year. (A same-year batch transfer updates the existing row's `batch_id`/`branch_id` and logs the change via Activity Log, Module 14, rather than creating a second enrollment row for the same year.)

**Worked example — Class Promotion across a year (Section 5.3):**

| id | student_id | academic_year_id | branch_id | class | batch_id | status | previous_enrollment_id |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| E-101 | S-001 | 2025–26 | Baguipara | 11 | `11 JEE` | Completed | — |
| E-204 | S-001 | 2026–27 | Baguipara | 12 | `12 JEE A` | Active | E-101 |

Querying `Student S-001`'s full history is now: `SELECT * FROM Enrollment WHERE student_id = 'S-001' ORDER BY academic_year_id` — no field was overwritten, nothing was lost, and the `previous_enrollment_id` chain shows exactly when and how the student moved.

Every other module that today says "Student" for attendance, exams, results, report cards, and fees (Sections 2, 8) should key off **`enrollment_id`**, not `student_id` directly — that's what keeps a student's Class 11 attendance record from ever being confused with their Class 12 attendance record once both exist in the same table.
